  "text": "Our identification of singing CPG neurons in Gryllus bimaculatus highlights the importance of ganglion A3. The data provide the basis for further studies to establish the functional circuitry of the network and to reveal evolutionary modifications in the singing CPG that account for the distinctive calling song patterns in related cricket species [CITATION_1] . Moreover, the connection between the singing CPG and the corollary discharge interneuron that modulates auditory processing during sound production Hedwig 2002, 2006 ) may now be targeted.",
